  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it’s a reality that’s been digging in my bones since I was a kid, even though I never had the chance to study engineering or physics. Growing up in a small town where most of my friends were kids who’d never seen a computer beyond a basic calculator, I remember being told by teachers that math was for 'some people,' not for me. My dad, who had a master’s degree but worked as a mechanic, always said, 'You can do anything if you just try hard enough,' but I felt like that was just wishful thinking. Now, at 65, I still see the same patterns: women and people of color who are trying to get into STEM fields often feel like they’re failing before they even start. The problem isn’t just about the stereotypes themselves—it’s about how they make people feel like they don’t belong. I’ve seen it in my own life too, like when I tried to learn coding last year for fun; I kept second-guessing myself because I thought I wasn’t smart enough. Addressing stereotype threat isn’t about fixing people—it’s about changing the environment so that people don’t have to hide their potential. For me, it’s about creating spaces where people feel safe to try without fear of judgment. That means teachers and mentors who know the history of discrimination in STEM and who act like they’re on the same team as the student. It’s also about making sure that everyone has access to the resources they need, like free coding classes or mentorship programs that don’t assume you’re already 'qualified.' I’ve been depressed for years, and I know how important it is to feel like you belong. If we don’t address stereotype threat, more people will give up before they even get started, and that’s a loss for everyone. It’s not just about the numbers—it’s about the people.",
